ister provided this funding update as promised, and will she\ncommit to increasing their operating funding today? ","index":"00227","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Hon.\nRochelle </b><b><a name=\"_Toc67040014\">Squires</a></b><b>�(Minister of Families):</b> Our government is very proud to have worked\nshoulder-to-shoulder with the child-care sector. That is why we have increased\ntheir budget by $20&nbsp;million since we formed office, more money�$20 million\nmore than the NDP ever invested in child care, for a grand total of\n$181&nbsp;million this year. And we also have created 4,000 new spaces. ","index":"00228","speaker":"Rochelle Squires"},{"html":"����� I've\ntalked to many parents who have told me about their need to get into child care\nand more flexible, adaptive child care. That is why we've created 4,000 fully\nfunded spaces since we formed govern�ment. ","index":"00229","speaker":""},{"html":"����� And we\nknow that more work needs to be done and we're committed to doing that work. ","index":"00230","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Madam\nSpeaker:</b> The honourable member for Thompson, on a supplementary question. ","index":"00231","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Ms. Adams:</b> Not only is the minister refusing to deliver on her\npromise to update the child-care centres about funding, but the lack of\ntransparency and the push towards privatization in our child-care sector is\ncausing anxiety with Manitobans. ","index":"00232","speaker":"Danielle Adams"},{"html":"����� The proposed legislation has no increase for ECEs<b> </b>and no\ndirect investment for early-childhood�child-care centres. Instead, the primary\ngoal of Bill 47 is to give public dollars to private, for-profit child-care\ncentres. ","index":"00233","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Why is\nthe minister trying to give away public dollars for for-profit centres and not\ninvesting in our non-profit sector? ","index":"00234","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Ms. Squires:</b> It's really unfortunate to see that member follow